Geometry, R, Stan, and NFL Field Goal Attempts: 1960-2019

James R Bland (https://sites.google.com/site/jamesbland/)

November 23, 2019

In a recent blog post, I downloaded data on every NFL field goal attempt since 1960, as recorded by pro-football-reference.com. For this post, I am going to take a model of angle accuracy to the data, which will be similar to my previous post on NBA jump shots, and Andrew Gelman’s model of golf putting.

Here is a summary of what I downloaded (more details in the previous blog post):

AggData<-aggregate(Data[,c("Dist","Y","B")],by=list(Data$Dist),FUN=mean)

AggData$count<-aggregate(Data[,c("Dist")], by=list(Data$Dist),FUN=length)$x
AggData<-AggData[AggData$Dist<=65,]
plt<-ggplot(AggData,aes(x=Dist,y=Y,size=count))+geom_smooth(method="loess")+xlab("Distance to goal (yards)")+ylab("Probability of success")+geom_point(alpha=0.5)+ylim(0,1)
plt<-plt+theme_bw()
plt

Model

A player makes a field goal attempt \(x\) yards from the goal (my data). The goal posts are \(d\) yards apart (given), and the crossbar is \(h\) yards above the ground (I attempted to use this too, but there are not enough long shots to identify the parameters for this model, see Appendix II).

Let \(y\) be the hypotenuse of the right-angled triangle made between the ball, the midpoint of the goalposts, and one of the goal posts. This hypotenuse has length: \(y=\sqrt{x^2+d^2/4}\). The angle at the ball vertex of this triangle can be found by solving: \[ \begin{aligned} x&=y\cos\theta\\ x&=\cos\theta\sqrt{x^2+d^2/4}\\ \cos\theta&=\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+d^2/4}}\\ \theta&=\cos^{-1}\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+d^2/4}}\right) \end{aligned} \] And hence the angle of tolerance for a field goal at the \(x\)-yard line is \(\pm\theta\).

Now suppose that the actual angle of a kick, where \(\theta=0\) corresponds to a straight kick, is distributed \(N(0,\kappa)\). The probability of getting the angle right on a kick is therefore: \[ \Pr\left(\text{angle good} \mid x,\kappa\right)=1-2\Phi\left(\kappa^{-1}\cos^{-1}\left(\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+d^2/4}}\right)\right) \]

This model has one parameter, \(\kappa\), which must be positive. I use \(\log\kappa \sim N(\pi,1)\) the prior.

Estimating the model in Stan

One learning experience for me here was that Stan works much faster with count data (i.e. one row summarizes all successes and failures at 40 yards), rather than binary (i.e. each row is one attempt). So here is what I ended up with, but it’s not where I started.

// FieldGoalsCount.stan
functions {
   
              
}
data {
  // Tell Stan how to read in the data
  int n; // Number of observations
  vector[n] Angle; 
  int y[n]; // =count of scored
  int N[n]; // number of attempts from that distance
  real priorK[2];
  
}
transformed data {
    
}
parameters {
  real<lower=0> k;

}
transformed parameters {
  
}
model {
    vector[n] p;
    for (ii in 1:n) {
        p[ii] =  1-2*normal_cdf((-Angle[ii]),0.0,k);
        
    }   


  y ~ binomial(N,p);


  }
generated quantities {

}

Results

Using all the data at once

Here are the estimation results if I use all data at once:

hist(extract(FitALL)$k)

But it is more helpful to see what this means in terms of predicted probabilities.

k<-extract(FitALL)$k
kq1<-quantile(k,c(0.025,0.975))
kq2<-quantile(extract(FitALL)$k,c(0.25,0.75))
km<-median(k)
x<-seq(1,80)

pltData<-data.frame(x)
pltData$angle<-acos(x/sqrt(x^2+d^2/4))
pltData$pm<-1-2*pnorm(-pltData$angle/km)
pltData$p1l<-1-2*pnorm(-pltData$angle/kq1[1])
pltData$p1u<-1-2*pnorm(-pltData$angle/kq1[2])
pltData$p2l<-1-2*pnorm(-pltData$angle/kq2[1])
pltData$p2u<-1-2*pnorm(-pltData$angle/kq2[2])
plt<-ggplot(pltData,aes(x=x,y=pm))
plt<-plt+geom_line()
plt<-plt+geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=p2l,ymax=p2u),alpha=0.5)
plt<-plt+geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=p1l,ymax=p1u),alpha=0.2)
plt<-plt+theme_bw()
plt<-plt+geom_point(data=AggData,aes(x=Dist,y=Y,size=count),alpha=0.5)
plt<-plt+xlab("Distance to goal (yards)")+ylab("Probability of success")
plt

So it looks like the model fits pretty well in the 20-40 yards range (where most of the kicks are taken), but does not do so well outside there.

Estimating the model for each season separately

I also estimate the model for each season individually. This way, we can see how kicking has improved over time.

AD<-aggregate(Data[,c("season","Dist","Y")],by=list(Data$season,Data$Dist),FUN=mean)
AD$count<-aggregate(Data[,c("season","Dist","Y")],by=list(Data$season,Data$Dist),FUN=length)$Y
AD<-AD[,c("season","Dist","Y","count")]
AD$x<-AD$Dist
pltData<-data.frame()
SeasonList<-seq(1960,2019)
for (xx in 1:length(x)) {
  a<-acos(x[xx]/sqrt(x[xx]^2+d^2/4))
  p<-data.frame(aggregate(SimSeason[,c("k","season")],by=list(SimSeason$season),FUN=function(z) mean(1-2*pnorm(-a/z))))$k
  pl<-data.frame(aggregate(SimSeason[,c("k","season")],by=list(SimSeason$season),FUN=function(z) quantile(1-2*pnorm(-a/z),0.025)))$k
pu<-data.frame(aggregate(SimSeason[,c("k","season")],by=list(SimSeason$season),FUN=function(z) quantile(1-2*pnorm(-a/z),0.975)))$k
  tmp<-data.frame(p,pl,pu)
  tmp$season<-SeasonList
  tmp$x<-x[xx]
  #
  
  
  pltData<-rbind(pltData,tmp)
  
}

pD<-merge(pltData,AD,by=c("season","x"),all=TRUE)


plt<-ggplot(pD,aes(x=x,y=p))+geom_line(color="blue",size=2)
plt<-plt+geom_ribbon(aes(x=x,ymin=pl,ymax=pu),color="blue",fill="blue",alpha=0.5)
plt<-plt+xlab("Distance to goal (yards)")+ylab("Probability of success")
plt<-plt+geom_point(aes(x=x,y=Y,size=count),alpha=0.5)
plt<-plt+transition_time(season)
plt<-plt+xlab("Distance to goal (yards)")+ylab("Probability of success")
plt<-plt+theme_bw()
plt<-plt+labs(title = 'Season: {frame_time}')
animate(plt, nframes = length(SeasonList)*2)

The shaded area around the line is a 95% Bayesian credible region (2.5th-97.5th percentile). So just like the pooled model, these models are doing well for the most common distances, and doing especially terribly for the long shots. In Appendix II I discuss a possible extension, but there are not much data that far away from the goal, so there isn’t much to be learned there.

Comparing the first and most recent (completed) season in the data, there has been considerable improvement!

pltData<-rbind(pD[pD$season==2018,],pD[pD$season==1960,])
pltData$season<-paste(pltData$season)
plt<-ggplot(pltData,aes(x=x,y=p,color=season,group=season,fill=season))+geom_line(size=2)
plt<-plt+geom_ribbon(aes(x=x,ymin=pl,ymax=pu),alpha=0.5)
plt<-plt+xlab("Distance to goal (yards)")+ylab("Probability of success")
plt<-plt+geom_point(aes(x=x,y=Y,size=count),alpha=0.5)

Estimating the model for each player separately

Finally. I can estimate the model by each player. There are over 400 of them (about 300 after I exclude those who only made 10 or fewer attempts), so I will focus on ranking the players based on their estimated probability of scoring at 50 yards.

SimPlayer$Pr50<-1-2*pnorm(-acos(50/sqrt(50^2+d^2/4))/SimPlayer$k)
PlayerMeans<-aggregate(SimPlayer,by=list(SimPlayer$Player),FUN= mean)
PlayerMeans$Player<-PlayerMeans$Group.1
PlayerMeans$sd<-aggregate(SimPlayer,by=list(SimPlayer$Player),FUN= sd)$Pr50
Sorted<-PlayerMeans[order(PlayerMeans$Pr50),]
Sorted$rank<-seq(1:dim(Sorted)[1])

plt<-ggplot(Sorted,aes(x=rank,y=Pr50,ymin=(Pr50-sd),ymax=(Pr50+sd),color=season))+geom_point()
plt<-plt+geom_errorbar()
plt<-plt+theme_bw()+xlab("rank (higher is better)")+ylab("Probability at 50 yards")
plt

Here, “season” is equal to the year in which a player first made a field goal attempt in the NFL. The error bars show \(\pm1\) posterior standard deviation.

D<-Data #[Data$season==2011,]
DCount<-aggregate(D,by=list(D$Dist),FUN=length)
N<-DCount$Y
y<-aggregate(D,by=list(D$Dist),FUN=mean)$Y*N
Angle<-aggregate(D,by=list(D$Dist),FUN=mean)$Angle

StanData<-list(Angle=Angle,y=as.integer(y),N=N,n=length(Angle),priorK=c(log(pi),1))

## BY SEASON
SeasonList<-unique(Data$season)
SimSeason<-data.frame()
for (ss in 1:length(SeasonList)) {
  D<-Data[Data$season==SeasonList[ss],]
  DCount<-aggregate(D,by=list(D$Dist),FUN=length)
  N<-DCount$Y
  y<-aggregate(D,by=list(D$Dist),FUN=mean)$Y*N
  Angle<-aggregate(D,by=list(D$Dist),FUN=mean)$Angle
  Distance<-aggregate(D,by=list(D$Dist),FUN=mean)$Dist
  StanData<-list(Angle=Angle,y=as.integer(y),N=N,n=length(Angle),priorK=c(log(pi),1))
  Fit<-stan("FieldGoalsCount.stan",data=StanData,seed=42,control = list(adapt_delta = 0.8))
  k<-extract(Fit, permuted = TRUE)$k
  tmp<-data.frame(k)
  tmp$season<-SeasonList[ss]
  SimSeason<-rbind(SimSeason,tmp)
  print(paste("---",SeasonList[ss],"---",ss,"of",length(SeasonList)))
} 
saveRDS(SimSeason,"NFLFieldGoalsData/SimSeason.rds")

    N<-DCount$Y

    Angle<-aggregate(D,by=list(D$Dist),FUN=mean)$Angle

    StanData<-list(Angle=Angle,y=as.integer(y),N=N,n=length(Angle),priorK=c(log(pi),1))
    Fit<-stan("FieldGoalsCount.stan",data=StanData,seed=42,control = list(adapt_delta = 0.8))
    k<-extract(Fit, permuted = TRUE)$k
    tmp<-data.frame(k)
    tmp$Player<-PlayerList[ss]
    tmp$count<-dim(D)[1]
    tmp$season<-min(D$season)
    SimPlayer<-rbind(SimPlayer,tmp)
    print(paste("---",PlayerList[ss],"---",ss,"of",length(PlayerList),"---",dim(D)[1]))
  }
}

APPENDIX I: an extension that didn’t work

Suppose that the ball is kicked directly[^1] at the goal at speed \(v\) (yards per second) and angle \(\rho\). Assuming zero wind resistance, the position of the ball at time \(t\) is: \[ x(t)=vt\cos\rho,\quad y(t)=vt\sin\rho-\frac{g}{2}t^2 \] From here, I calculate the last time the ball is above the height of the crossbar, and use this to work out if it is before or after passing through the goalposts \[ \begin{aligned} h&=vt_h\sin\rho-\frac g2 t_h^2\\ t_h&=\frac{v\sin\rho+\sqrt{v^2\sin^2\rho-2gh}}{g}\\ x_h&=vt_h\cos\rho\\ &=\frac{v^2\cos\rho\sin\rho+v\cos\rho\sqrt{v^2\sin^2\rho-2gh}}{g} \end{aligned} \] I need to assign a probability distribution over \(v\) (more on that later), evaluate whether \(x_h\) happens before (bad) or after (good) the ball passes through the goal posts. That is, the probability of getting the height right is \(\Pr(x<x_h)\), where \(x_h\) is a (messy) function of random variable \(v\). This would be made much easier if I could approximate the square root term. Here I need to get some data to work out what an appropriate approximation is. according to sportsrec.com a college football kickers typically achieve speeds of \(v=60 \mathrm{mph}\times \frac{1760 \mathrm{\ yards} / \mathrm{mile}}{3600\ \mathrm s / \mathrm h}\approx 29 \mathrm{\ yards\ s}^{-1}\), so with \(2gh=2\times 10.7\mathrm{\ yards /s}^2*(10/3) \mathrm{\ yards}\approx 71\), and \(v^2\sin^2\rho\approx 29^2/2=420.5\) (setting \(\rho=\pi/4\)), the first term is probably going to dominate. Hence: \[ \begin{aligned} \sqrt{v^2\sin^2\rho-2gh}&\approx \sqrt{v^2\sin^2\rho}=v\sin\rho \end{aligned} \]

Checking this approximation

v<-seq(0,100,1)
x<-sqrt(v^2/2-71)
d1<-data.frame(v,x)
d1$f<-"actual function"
v<-seq(0,100,1)
x<-sqrt(v^2/2)
d2<-data.frame(v,x)
d2$f<-"approximation"
d<-rbind(d1,d2)
d<-d[is.nan(d$x)==FALSE,]
plt<-ggplot(data=d,aes(x=v,y=x,color=f))+theme_bw()+geom_line()
plt

So it is not too terrible for reasonable kick speeds for college players, so it should work even better for NFL players. With the approximation, this becomes: \[ \begin{aligned} x_h&\approx\frac{v^2\cos\rho\sin\rho+v^2\sin\rho\cos\rho}{g}\\ &=v^2\frac{\sin\rho\cos\rho}{g} \end{aligned} \]

So the probability that the kick is above the crossbar at the right time is: \[ \begin{aligned} \Pr(x<x_h)&=\Pr\left(x<v^2\frac{\sin\rho\cos\rho}{g}\right)\\ &=\Pr\left(v>\sqrt{\frac{gx}{\sin\rho\cos\rho}}\right)\\ &=1-F_v\left(\sqrt{\frac{gx}{\sin\rho\cos\rho}}\right) \end{aligned} \] where \(F_v(\cdot)\) is the cdf of the distribution of \(v\). I let this be \(\log v \sim N(m,s^2)\). This allows the probability of success to look something like this:

x<-seq(17,80,1)
k<-1000
m<-log(35)
s<-0.05
# Distance between goal posts 18 feet 6 inches
d<-18.5/3
angle<-acos(x/sqrt(x^2+d^2/4))
pd<-data.frame(x,k,angle)
pd$PrAngle<-1-2*pbeta((-angle+pi/2)/pi, 0.5*k, 0.5*k)
pd$PrHeight<-1-pnorm(log(sqrt(10.7*x/0.5)),m,s)
pd$PrTotal<-pd$PrHeight*pd$PrAngle
pltdata<-pd

plt<-ggplot()+geom_line(data=pltdata,aes(x=x,y=PrTotal,color="Total"),size=2)+theme_bw()
plt<-plt+geom_line(data=pltdata,aes(x=x,y=PrHeight,color="Height"))+geom_line(data=pltdata,aes(x=x,y=PrAngle,color="Angle"))
plt

That is, success at close range is mostly about getting the angle right, and success at long range is mostly about distance. Furthermore, distance has the greatest marginal effect of this second probability at: \[ \begin{aligned} 0&=\sqrt{\frac{gx}{\sin\rho\cos\rho}}-m\\ m^2\sin\rho\cos\rho&=gx\\ x=\frac{m^2\sin\rho\cos\rho}{g} \end{aligned} \]

The trouble I was having with this model was that so few attempts are made further than about 60 yards out. Even when I pooled the data from all years and all players, there was very little information about these parameters (and the predictions were terrible).
